Task 1 — Create the Jira Project (Team-managed → Scrum)
Steps:

Log in to Jira Cloud → https://your-domain.atlassian.net
In the sidebar, next to Spaces (or top navigation Projects), click Create space (or + Create project if visible).
Choose team-managed (select "Select a team-managed space" or similar).
Under templates, choose Scrum (or Software → Scrum if options shown).
Enter:
Name: DevOps Micro-Internship Website – George
Key: DMIWEB (or auto)

Set Access: Private
Skip "Bring your team along" / invite step.
Click Create.

Screenshot 1: Confirmation screen after creation, or sidebar / header showing project name + key (DMIWEB).


Task 2 — Create Your First Epic (From Backlog)
Steps:

Open your new project (click it in sidebar or Spaces list).
Go to Backlog (left sidebar).
If not visible: enable Backlog in Project settings → Features → toggle Backlog ON.
In Backlog view, look for Epic panel (left side or toggle "Epic" / "Epics panel" ON if hidden).
Click + Create Epic (or similar button in Epic panel).
Epic Name: Polish DMI Website UI & Deploy
Add a short Summary / Description if prompted.
Create.

Notes:
Epics group related stories for big deliverables. The Epic panel helps visualize progress.
Screenshots:

Screenshot 2: Backlog view with Epic panel ON and your new Epic visible in the panel.

Task 3 — Seed the Product Backlog (6 Stories under the Epic + Fibonacci points)
Steps:

In Backlog, click Create issue (or + button).
Issue Type: Story
Parent / Epic link: select "Polish DMI Website UI & Deploy"
Assign to yourself.
Fill Story point estimate (open issue after create if needed → add to Story Points field).
Add Description + Acceptance Criteria (use Gherkin format in Description or dedicated AC field if available).
Add Labels (type in Labels field).
Repeat for all 6.

Stories to create (copy-paste):

S1 — Update site header text (2 pts)
Description: Change top header to: “DevOps Micro-Internship — Learn by Building”
Acceptance Criteria:
Given I open the homepage, when the page loads, then the header shows exactly “DevOps Micro-Internship — Learn by Building”.
And the change is visible on the EC2 URL (pending).
Labels: frontend
S2 — Primary button color refresh (2 pts)
Description: Update primary button color (e.g., #0d6efd) for a cleaner look.
AC:
Given the homepage loads, when I view any primary button, then its background reflects the new color and text remains readable (AA contrast or better).
And visible on EC2 (pending).
Labels: frontend
S3 — Improve hero subtitle copy (1 pt)
Description: Replace hero subtitle with: “Practice real DevOps workflows — Git, CI/CD, Cloud, and deployments.”
AC:
Given the hero area loads, then the subtitle appears exactly as above and fits on one line on desktop.
Labels: frontend
S4 — Footer with version & date (2 pts)
Description: Add footer text: “DMI Website v1.0 — Deployed on ” (static text is fine).
AC:
Given I scroll to the footer, then I see the version and a human-readable date.
Labels: devops
S5 — Add “Contact / About” section (2 pts)
Description: Add a small section showing Name + Email + Community link (use placeholders).
AC:
Given I open the homepage, then I see a section with contact details (or placeholders) clearly visible.
Labels: frontend
S6 — Add “Join DMI” call-to-action (1 pt)
Description: Add a CTA button/link: “Join the DMI Waitlist” (can link to placeholder #).
AC:
Given the homepage loads, then I see a CTA “Join the DMI Waitlist” and it is clickable.
Labels: frontend

Notes:
All stories linked to the Epic, estimated, with clear AC in Gherkin.
Screenshots:

Screenshot 3: Backlog showing Epic + all 6 stories indented/grouped under it.
Screenshot 4: One opened story (e.g. S1 or S2) showing Story Points, AC text, Label applied.

Task 4 — Add Sub-tasks to at Least 2 Stories
Steps:

Open story (e.g. S2).
Under story title / details → click + Create sub-task (or child work item).
Create these 4 sub-tasks (estimate 2–6 hours or leave blank):
Edit HTML/CSS (make the change)
Test locally (browser check)
Deploy to EC2 (copy/upload)
Verify & screenshot (capture EC2 URL)

Repeat exactly for S4.

Notes:
Sub-tasks break stories into actionable steps.
Screenshots:

Screenshot 5: S2 opened, showing all 4 sub-tasks listed under it.
Screenshot 6: S4 opened, showing all 4 sub-tasks.

Task 5 — Tag Stories by Workstream (Labels)
Steps:

Open each story → edit → add Labels if missing.
Confirm:
S1, S2, S3, S5, S6: frontend
S4: devops


Notes:
Labels enable filtering by area (frontend vs devops).
Screenshots:

Screenshot 7: Backlog or issue view showing at least 2 stories with labels visible (e.g. filter applied or details pane).

Task 6 — Create Sprint 1 (1 week) + Set Sprint Goal + Start Sprint
Steps:

In Backlog, click Create sprint (or + Sprint button).
Name: Sprint 1
Drag 2–3 stories into it (suggest: S1 (2), S3 (1), S6 (1) — total 4 pts; or any combo ~3–5 pts).
Click into sprint details → set Sprint Goal: “Ship visible DMI Website UI polish (header, color, footer/CTA) to EC2 with screenshots.”
Click Start sprint (choose 1 week duration if prompted).

Notes:
Goal keeps focus. Board now shows active sprint.
Screenshots:

Screenshot 8: Backlog with Sprint 1 created, stories inside, points total visible.
Screenshot 9: Active sprint / board view showing Sprint Goal.

Task 7 — Use Filters to View Stories + Subtasks + Status
Steps:

In Backlog or Board → use quick filters or search bar.
Filter examples:
label = frontend → shows S1,S2,S3,S5,S6
label = devops → shows S4
Has sub-tasks (if filter available, or search "has:sub-tasks")

Observe filtered results.

Notes:
Daily filtering helps focus on workstreams.
Screenshots:

Screenshot 10: Backlog/Board with label=frontend filter applied (showing results).
Screenshot 11: Same with label=devops filter.

Task 8 — Open Burndown Report (for later tracking)
Steps:

In project sidebar → Reports (if not visible: Project settings → Features → toggle Reports ON).
Select Burndown Chart (or Sprint Burndown).
Choose Sprint 1 (may show flat line since just started — normal).

Notes:
Burndown tracks remaining work. It populates as you log progress.
Screenshots:

Screenshot 12: Burndown Chart page open for Sprint 1.

Final Tips for Submission:

Create Google Doc named: George_DMI_Jira_Setup (or similar).
Use exact structure from the assignment.
Paste notes + screenshots under each task.
Set sharing: Anyone with the link → Viewer or Commenter.
Test link in incognito mode.
If any UI differs slightly (Atlassian updates labels occasionally), follow the closest equivalent (e.g., "space" vs "project", toggle features in settings).
